### Problem13
S​uppose you want to add a constructor to Complex that takes a double value as its argument and creates a Complex number with that value as the real part (and imaginary part equal to 0). You write the following code:

```java
public void Complex(double real)
{
    re = real;
    im = 0.0;
}
```

B​ut then the statement Complex c = new Complex(1.0) does not compile. Why?

**Choices:**

T​he types of re and im are not declared.

A​ class can only have one constructor.

C​onstructors do not have return types, not even void.

T​he return type should be Complex, not void.

N​one of the above.
